We see that Assault has a much larger variance than the other variables. It would dominate the Prinicple components, so we choose to standardise the variables when we perform PCA.

pca.out = prcomp(USArrests, scale=TRUE)

K-Means Clustering

K means works in any dimensions, but is most fun to demonstrate in two, because we can plot pictures. Lets make some data with clusters. We do this by shifting the means of the points around.

set.seed(101)
x=matrix(rnorm(100^2),100,2)
xmean = matrix(rnorm(8,sd=4),4,2)
which= sample(1:4,100,replace=TRUE)
x=x+xmean[which,]
plot(x,col=which,pch=19)

We know the “true” cluster IDs, but we wont tell that to the kmeans algotithms.

km.out=kmeans(x,4,nstart=15)
km.out
## K-means clustering with 4 clusters of sizes 20, 20, 32, 28
## 
## Cluster means:

plot(x,col=km.out$cluster,cex=2,pch=1,lwd=2)

plot(x,col=which,pch=19)
points(x,col=c(4,3,2,1)[which],pch=19)

Hierarchical Clustering

We will use these same data and use hierachical clustering

hc.complete=hclust(dist(x),method="complete")
plot(hc.complete)

hc.single=hclust(dist(x),method = "single")
plot(hc.single)

hc.average=hclust(dist(x),method = "average")
plot(hc.average)

Lets compare this with the actually clustering in the data. We will use the function cuttree to cut the tree at level 4. This will produce a vector of number from 1 to 4, saying which branch each obeservation is on. You will sometimes see preety plots where the leaves of the dendogram are colored. I searched a bit on the web for how to do this, and its a little too complecated for this demonstration.

We can use the table to see how well they match:

hc.cut=cutree(hc.complete,4)
table(hc.cut,which)
##       which
## hc.cut  1  2  3  4
##      1 33  0  0  0
##      2  0  0 18  1
##      3  0 27  0  0
##      4  0  0  4 17
table(hc.cut,km.out$cluster)
##       
## hc.cut  1  2  3  4
##      1  0  0 32  1
##      2  0 19  0  0
##      3  0  0  0 27
##      4 20  1  0  0

or we can use out group membership as labels for the leaves of the dendograms:

plot(hc.complete,labels = which)
